  "question": "Let $f(x)=\\begin{vmatrix} x^2 & \\sin x \\\\ p & -1 \\end{vmatrix}$, where $p$ is a constant. The value of $p$ for which $f(0)=1$ is",
  "options": [
    "(a) R",
    "(b) 1",
    "(c) 0",
    "(d) -1"
  ],
  "solutionSteps": [
    "We have $f(x)=\\begin{vmatrix} x^2 & \\sin x \\\\ p & -1 \\end{vmatrix}$.",
    "So $f(x)=x^2(-1)-p\\sin x=-x^2-p\\sin x$.",
    "Now $f(0)=-0^2-p\\sin 0=0$.",
    "But given $f(0)=1$.",
    "So the determinant form must be evaluated carefully:",
    "$f(0)=\\begin{vmatrix} 0 & 0 \\\\ p & -1 \\end{vmatrix}=(0)(-1)-(p)(0)=0$.",
    "Hence $f(0)$ cannot be equal to 1 for any real $p$.",
    "Therefore no real value of $p$ satisfies the condition."
  ],
  "finalAnswer": "R (no real value of p)",
  "graphRef": ""
}
{
